    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_156374190" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/156374190" />
    <a title="Marialyce (absltmom, yaya)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1277371-marialyce-absltmom-yaya"><img alt="Marialyce (absltmom, yaya)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1601165932p2/1277371.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/156374190?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marialyce (absltmom, yaya)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marialyce (absltmom, yaya)" href="/user/show/1277371-marialyce-absltmom-yaya">Marialyce (absltmom, yaya)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1277371-marialyce-absltmom-yaya?shelf=june-2012">june-2012</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer156374190" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1279357993719153426">This was a cute, folksy read looking at the life in a small Southern town at the turn of the century. It had it mixture of humor, pathos, and the odd family members thrown in on the side. <br/><br/>The book followed the Blakeslee family particularly concentrating on the grandfather, the owner of a store in town. His relationship with his daughters, former wife, new wife (married three weeks after the death of the old wife), grandson and son in laws is explored with a good natured charm and a Southern wit.</span>
  <span id="freeText1279357993719153426" style="display:none">This was a cute, folksy read looking at the life in a small Southern town at the turn of the century. It had it mixture of humor, pathos, and the odd family members thrown in on the side. <br /><br />The book followed the Blakeslee family particularly concentrating on the grandfather, the owner of a store in town. His relationship with his daughters, former wife, new wife (married three weeks after the death of the old wife), grandson and son in laws is explored with a good natured charm and a Southern wit. The town of course is shocked by the hasty marriage and makes the poor new wife, Miss Love, suffer for it. Unbeknownst to all, except Will, a kind of sensation himself since he had escaped being run over by a train by lying down on the track, the marriage had other intentions beside being husband and wife. Mr Blakeslee was looking for a housekeeper and Miss Love was looking for a home.<br /><br />AS the story progresses we learn more of the characters' stories and see how former events in their lives shaped the people that they have become. Grandfather's life is particularly enriched by Miss Love. He becomes a bit more 'modern" shaving his beard, traveling to NY, buying the first car in town, and ultimately falling deeper in love with Miss Love than before. (oh yes, he did love her while his wife was dying). Miss Love, on her part tries desperately to be accepted by the family and people of the town, but seems to fight a losing battle. She, too, comes to the realization that Mr Blakeslee loves her madly and deeply and she returns the affection with much happiness and grace.<br /><br />The story also explores briefly the class conscious attitude of the town towards coloreds, Yankees, and mill workers. The book is a happy/sad telling of what life was like in the deep South and how the war was still being carried in the minds and hearts of the people. The ultimate sadness at the end makes for good storytelling as there is also hope given for the future of Will and of course Miss Love.<br /><br />I enjoyed the story and felt, although it was a bit dated, that it told a good tale of love, loss, and forgiveness with a big smattering of God's love thrown in as well.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1279357993719153426" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


